Reading data

 dirs <- list.dirs("path/to/cellranger_results", full.names=TRUE)
 names(dirs) <- basename(fastq_dirs)
 sce <- DropletUtils::read10xCounts(dirs)


To read data from alevin, see the tximport package

The SingleCellExperiment (SCE) class

Based on the SummarziedExperiment class:

The SingleCellExperiment (SCE) class

  • Single colData columns (cell properties) can be accessed through the $, or as a whole through colData(sce).
  • rowData for feature-level data
  • assays(sce) produces a list of assays; the SCE class also includes the counts(sce) (equivalent to assays(sce)$counts) and logcounts(sce) accessors for specific assays.
  • In addition, the SCE can hold information about low-dimensional representations, accessible as named list through reducedDims(sce)
  • Both classes are compatible with the interactive SE explorer iSEE !

more about SingleCellExperiment

Doublets

  • when >=2 cells get captured in the same droplet and are sequenced with a single cellular barcode
  • While doublets tend to have more reads than singlets, the difference is insufficient to flag them

Doublets

  • Doublets created from the same ‘type’, termed homotypic doublets, are nearly undetectable
  • neotypic or heterotypic doublets doublets, which combine cells of different types, are potentially problematic but fairly detectable
  • Most methods detect doublets through their similarity with artificially-created doublets:
    • scDblFinder is easy to use, efficient and accurate
    • For very large and complex datasets, scds is particularly fast and scalable
 BiocManager::install("testthat")
 BiocManager::install("plger/scDblFinder")

QC and filtering

  • The scater package is a handy tool for quality control and plotting, working with the SCE class.
  • In BioC <3.10, per-cell and per-gene statistics used to be compiled with calculateQCMetrics()
  • In devel (>=3.10), has been replaced with addQCPerCell() and addQCPerFeature()
  • isOutlier() can be used to determine cells whose given property is outside a given range from the median

QC and filtering

  • Stringent filters are heavily biased on some cell types
  • Cluster-based filters typically remove nothing

Seurat

  • Seurat uses its own object class for handling the data
  • The Seurat class can contain different assays, but each assay has 3 slots:
    • raw.data, data (normalized), and scale.data (normalized and scaled).
    • The data can be accessed as follows:
 GetAssayData(so, assay="RNA", slot="raw.data")



  • as with SCE, cell metadata can be accessed with $

Choosing number of dimensions

\(dist(a,b) = \sqrt{ (a_1-b_1)^2 + (a_2-b_2)^2 + ... + (a_k-b_k)^2}\)


Choosing number of dimensions

  • Example strategies:
    • finding elbow in variance explained
    • Seurats JackStraw procedure
    • scrans denoisePCA

Browsing clustering resolutions

See the clustree package

Cluster annotation

  • One can use a combination of:
    • relying on known markers
    • look for genes with cluster-specific expression patterns (see for instance Seurat::FindAllMarker or scran::findMarkers)
  • In addition, a variety of methods are being developed to recognize cell types from reference data (e.g. cellassign)
